Acute Uncomplicated Diverticulitis (AGA 2015 + 2022):

(1) Diagnosis: CT contrast preferred imaging (also assesses complications — abscess, perforation, fistula, obstruction); WBC + CRP;

(2) Classification: uncomplicated vs complicated (abscess, perforation, fistula, obstruction, peritonitis, hemorrhage);

(3) Treatment uncomplicated outpatient (selected patients):
  • Antibiotics — selective use (AGA 2015 update — not all patients need):
  • Consider observation without antibiotics in mild uncomplicated patients (AVOD + DIABOLO trials — no benefit antibiotic over supportive);
  • Reasonable: hospitalize / antibiotic if immunocompromised, comorbidity, elderly, complicated, can't tolerate PO, severe systemic;
  • If antibiotic — amoxicillin-clavulanate PO × 5-10 d (newer trials shorter courses) OR ciprofloxacin + metronidazole;
  • Hospital IV: ceftriaxone + metronidazole or pip-tazo;

(4) Diet: clear liquid early, advance as tolerated; no evidence prolonged restriction; no need to avoid nuts, seeds, popcorn long-term (historical myth);

(5) Follow-up + colonoscopy after acute episode:
  • Routine colonoscopy 4-8 wk after recovery for first episode in patients without recent colonoscopy — exclude malignancy (rates of CRC slightly elevated post-diverticulitis); evidence supports but some emerging modification for younger / clear-cut cases;

(6) Long-term management:
  • High-fiber diet + adequate hydration — recurrence prevention;
  • Physical activity + weight;
  • Avoid NSAIDs (perforation risk);
  • Smoking cessation;
  • Mesalamine + rifaximin + probiotics — limited evidence;

(7) Surgery (elective for recurrent or complicated, urgent for complications):
  • Elective sigmoidectomy — individualized based on recurrence frequency, severity, lifestyle impact, complicated episodes; previous threshold of 2 episodes no longer absolute (more individualized);
  • Complicated abscess: percutaneous drainage if > 4 cm; smaller may respond to antibiotics alone;
  • Perforation / peritonitis → urgent surgery (Hartmann's procedure traditional, primary anastomosis emerging);

(8) Complications watch:
  • Abscess;
  • Perforation (free air → emergency);
  • Fistula (colovesical most common — UTI, pneumaturia, fecaluria);
  • Obstruction;
  • Hemorrhage (separate diverticular bleed);

(9) Recurrence common (~ 30%);

(10) Multidisciplinary: PCP + GI + surgery + radiology + IR (drainage) + dietitian
