Microscopic Hematuria Workup (AUA 2020):

(1) Diagnosis: ≥ 3 RBC/HPF on properly collected midstream urine confirmed on 1 of 2 urinalyses;

(2) Risk stratification AUA 2020 (replaces prior age-based):
  • Low risk: women < 50, men < 40, never smoker, < 10 RBC/HPF, no risk factors → repeat UA within 6 mo; if hematuria persists → reclassify;
  • Intermediate risk: 50-60 yo women, 40-60 yo men, 10-30 pack-yr smoking, 11-25 RBC/HPF, other risk factors → cystoscopy + renal US;
  • High risk (this patient): > 60 yo, > 30 pack-yr smoker, > 25 RBC/HPF, gross hematuria → cystoscopy + CT urography (CTU) — best test for upper tract;

(3) Rule out first: UTI (treat + repeat), exercise, menstruation, sexual activity, trauma, GU procedure recent;

(4) Workup:
  • Urinalysis confirm;
  • Urine culture rule out UTI;
  • Urine cytology — limited utility primary; useful selected (high-risk + cytology positive → urgent workup);
  • Imaging:
  • CT urography — gold standard upper tract (high-risk);
  • Renal US + KUB — alternative if CT contraindication / pregnancy / younger;
  • MRI urography alternative;
  • Cystoscopy — bladder evaluation (>= intermediate risk);
  • Cr / BUN, BP;
  • Proteinuria, dysmorphic RBC, casts suggest glomerular cause → nephrology workup (BMP, UPC, ANA, complement, hepatitis serology, etc.);

(5) Causes:
  • Urologic (workup priorities high-risk): malignancy (bladder, kidney, prostate, urethra), stones, BPH, infection, trauma, polycystic kidney;
  • Nephrologic / glomerular: IgA nephropathy, thin BM disease, Alport, glomerulonephritis (post-infectious, lupus, vasculitis), other;
  • Other: medications (rifampin, NSAIDs), exercise;

(6) Smoking cessation — bladder cancer major risk;

(7) Follow-up negative workup: repeat UA periodically (annual) — many resolve spontaneously; consider repeat workup if persistent + change in risk; nephrology referral if glomerular features;

(8) Bladder cancer high index suspicion smoker + hematuria — don't dismiss;

(9) Anticoagulation: doesn't excuse workup — anticoagulant-related hematuria still needs evaluation if persistent;

(10) Multidisciplinary: PCP + urology + nephrology + radiology + smoking cessation
