Lumbar Radiculopathy / Sciatica Management (ACP + NASS):

(1) Diagnosis: history (radiating leg pain > back pain, dermatomal, exacerbated by Valsalva, sciatic stretch — SLR + crossed SLR), exam (neurologic — sensory, motor, reflexes); rule out cauda equina (saddle anesthesia, bladder/bowel) emergency;

(2) No imaging routinely first 4-6 wk unless red flags or progressive neuro deficit;

(3) Conservative management 4-6 wk first (most resolve within 3 mo without intervention):
  • Activity modification (avoid prolonged bed rest);
  • NSAIDs short-term;
  • PT — McKenzie method, core strengthening, neurodynamic mobilization;
  • Education + reassurance — favorable prognosis;
  • Heat / ice;
  • Avoid opioids as first-line (limited benefit + harms);
  • Gabapentin / pregabalin — modest evidence radicular pain (more for diabetic neuropathy);
  • Oral steroids — limited evidence for sciatica (METEOR trial — modest functional benefit);
  • Topical agents;
  • Acupuncture alternative;

(4) MRI lumbar indicated for:
  • Red flags (cauda equina, malignancy, infection, fracture);
  • Progressive neuro deficit;
  • Failed conservative ≥ 6 wk + considering interventional/surgical;
  • Atypical / suspicious;

(5) Epidural steroid injection (ESI):
  • Modest short-term benefit for radicular pain (NASS);
  • Transforaminal or interlaminar;
  • Image-guided (fluoroscopy / US);
  • 1-3 typically, no more than 3/yr;
  • Risks: rare but serious (infection, hematoma, paralysis with cervical TF approach);

(6) Surgery indications:
  • Cauda equina (emergent);
  • Progressive motor deficit (weakness);
  • Refractory disabling pain ≥ 6-12 wk + correlative imaging (microdiscectomy, decompression, sometimes fusion);
  • SPORT trial — surgery + conservative both effective long-term, surgery faster recovery;

(7) Yellow flags (psychosocial chronicity risk): fear-avoidance, depression, work issues — address;

(8) Return to activity + work modifications;

(9) Multimodal chronic if persistent — CBT, multidisciplinary pain program;

(10) Multidisciplinary: PCP + PT + pain medicine + spine surgery (ortho or neurosurgery) + behavioral health
