Bell's Palsy Management (AAN 2012 + AAO-HNS 2013):

(1) Diagnosis clinical: acute (< 72 h) peripheral CN VII palsy involving forehead (unlike central — preserves forehead); often unilateral; can include hyperacusis, decreased taste anterior 2/3 tongue, decreased lacrimation, postauricular pain;

(2) Differential — rule out before Bell's palsy diagnosis:
  • Central (stroke) — preserves forehead, other neuro deficits;
  • Lyme disease — bilateral facial palsy, endemic area, tick exposure, classic erythema migrans (50%) → serology (high prevalence area), treat doxycycline;
  • Ramsay Hunt syndrome (HZV) — vesicles in ear canal, severe pain, sometimes hearing loss / vertigo → acyclovir + steroid + urgent ENT;
  • Otitis media / mastoiditis;
  • Trauma / fracture;
  • Tumor (slowly progressive, recurrent, complete + atypical features → MRI);
  • Sarcoidosis, GBS, MS;

(3) Workup: clinical for typical; selected — Lyme serology endemic, HSV/VZV serology if vesicles, CBC, glucose, imaging if atypical/progressive/recurrent (MRI w/ contrast);

(4) Treatment — start within 72 h for best outcomes:
  • Prednisone 60 mg daily × 7 days then taper — Class I evidence (Engstrom, Sullivan); improves probability complete recovery;
  • Antiviral (acyclovir, valacyclovir) — controversial, possible modest benefit added to steroid in severe cases (Class II); use combination if severe (House-Brackmann ≥ IV) per some guidelines; not effective alone;
  • Eye care critical: lubricating drops daytime, ophthalmic ointment + taping/patch nighttime, eye protection; ophthalmology if persistent (risk corneal abrasion + ulceration);
  • Facial exercises / PT — may help recovery;

(5) Prognosis:
  • 70% complete recovery without treatment;
  • 85% with steroid;
  • Recovery 3 wk
  • 6 mo typically;
  • Persistent / synkinesis / facial spasm in 30%;
  • Worse prognosis: complete palsy, older, DM, HTN, taste loss, hyperacusis, postauricular pain severe;

(6) Refractory / no improvement:
  • Refer ENT / neurology / facial nerve specialist;
  • Electrodiagnostic studies (ENoG, EMG) 5-21 days post-onset for prognostic + decision on intervention;
  • Surgical decompression — selected severe nonimprovement (controversial);
  • Botox + selective neurectomy for late synkinesis;
  • Facial reanimation surgery;

(7) Recurrent or bilateral — investigate for underlying cause (Lyme, sarcoid, lymphoma, GBS);

(8) Pregnancy: 3x higher; usually 3rd trimester / immediate postpartum; treatment + close monitoring;

(9) Patient education + emotional support: facial appearance distressing;

(10) Multidisciplinary: PCP + neurology + ENT + ophthalmology + PT + facial nerve specialist (refractory) + mental health if needed
