Anaphylaxis — Emergency (AAAAI + WAO 2020):

(1) Diagnosis: rapid-onset (minutes to hours) of skin/mucosa involvement + ≥ 1 of (respiratory, hypotension/end-organ, GI, syncope); OR hypotension/respiratory after known allergen exposure;

(2) TRIGGER first-line: IM epinephrine — DO NOT DELAY:
  • 0.3-0.5 mg adults (0.01 mg/kg, max 0.5 mg) IM into vastus lateralis (anterolateral thigh) — best absorption;
  • 0.15 mg child < 30 kg;
  • Repeat q 5-15 min if no improvement (~ 30% need repeat);
  • SC less effective than IM;
  • IV epinephrine drip for refractory in monitored setting only — high arrhythmia risk if bolus;

(3) Position: supine + legs elevated if hypotensive; left lateral if pregnant; sitting if dyspnea;

(4) Adjunct therapies (after epinephrine, not as substitute):
  • Oxygen + airway support;
  • IV fluid crystalloid bolus (20-30 mL/kg adult or 10-20 mL/kg child);
  • H1 antihistamine (diphenhydramine, cetirizine) — symptom relief skin only, NOT life-saving;
  • H2 antihistamine (famotidine) — symptom relief;
  • Inhaled bronchodilator (albuterol) for bronchospasm;
  • Corticosteroid (methylprednisolone 1-2 mg/kg IV) — debated efficacy in preventing biphasic, some evidence not helpful; given still by many;

(5) Refractory anaphylaxis:
  • IV epinephrine drip;
  • Vasopressors (norepinephrine, vasopressin);
  • Glucagon 1-5 mg IV (especially beta-blocker-blocked patients);
  • Methylene blue refractory shock;

(6) Observation post-event:
  • 4-6 hours typical mild;
  • 8-24+ hours severe;
  • Biphasic reactions in 5-20% (most within 4-6 h, can be up to 72 h);
  • Disposition based on clinical + risk;

(7) Discharge planning:
  • Epinephrine auto-injector prescription (≥ 2 devices) — patient + family + school;
  • Education on use;
  • Anaphylaxis action plan;
  • Trigger avoidance counseling;
  • Allergy referral for trigger identification + further management;
  • Medical alert identification;
  • No discharge without epinephrine prescription;

(8) Allergist evaluation: skin testing, specific IgE, oral food challenge, drug challenge (selected), component-resolved diagnostics;

(9) Immunotherapy / desensitization:
  • Venom immunotherapy highly effective (hymenoptera);
  • Oral immunotherapy (peanut — Palforzia) FDA-approved 4-17 yo;
  • Drug desensitization for required medications;
  • Aeroallergen SCIT/SLIT for allergic rhinitis (may reduce systemic);

(10) Specific allergen counseling:
  • Food: read labels, restaurant communication, school plans;
  • Drug: medical alert, listed on chart, alternatives;
  • Insect: avoidance, removal techniques;
  • Latex: occupational + medical;
  • Idiopathic anaphylaxis approach;

(11) Comorbidity: asthma well-controlled (highest mortality), mast cell disease (mastocytosis);

(12) Multidisciplinary: PCP + ED + allergy/immunology + emergency response + family + school + pharmacy
