Rectal Bleeding (BRBPR) Workup (AGA + ACG):

(1) History: characterize bleeding (with/separate from stool, amount, color), associated (pain, itching, discharge, mass, change in bowel habits, weight loss, family history CRC, IBD, smoking, NSAIDs);

(2) Exam: general, abdominal, rectal (inspection + DRE — fissures, hemorrhoids, masses, sphincter tone); anoscopy (in office) for direct visualization;

(3) Causes BRBPR:
  • Hemorrhoids — most common (internal painless, external painful if thrombosed);
  • Anal fissure — painful (tearing pain during BM, sentinel tag posterior most common, anterior may indicate trauma/Crohn's);
  • Polyps — usually painless;
  • Diverticular bleeding (typically intermittent, painless, larger volume);
  • Colitis (IBD, ischemic, infectious, radiation);
  • Colorectal cancer (must rule out — esp older, anemia, weight loss);
  • Anorectal trauma (sexual, foreign body, instrumentation);
  • Proctitis (radiation, STI, IBD);
  • Angiodysplasia (typically right colon, painless);
  • Solitary rectal ulcer;

