  • Age ≥ 40-45 with rectal bleeding (lower threshold age 40 emerging);
  • Age < 40: if persistent / recurrent, red flags (anemia, weight loss, family history, change in bowel habits), uncertain source — colonoscopy; if low risk + clear hemorrhoidal cause + responds to treatment → conservative + repeat eval if persistent;
  • Anemia present;
  • Suspicion of malignancy;
  • This patient at age 50 — colonoscopy indicated;

(5) Hemorrhoid management:
  • Conservative: high-fiber diet + adequate fluid + sitz baths + topical (hydrocortisone, lidocaine); avoid straining + prolonged toilet; address constipation;
  • Office procedures: rubber band ligation (most effective), sclerotherapy, infrared coagulation;
  • Surgery (hemorrhoidectomy) for severe / Grade IV / refractory;
  • Thrombosed external — excision within 48-72 h if very painful; otherwise conservative;

(6) Anal fissure management:
  • Acute — sitz bath + bulk laxative + topical analgesic; usually heal;
  • Chronic — topical nitroglycerin / diltiazem / nifedipine; botox; sphincterotomy if refractory;

(7) STI proctitis screening for receptive anal sex + risk factors — NAAT chlamydia/gonorrhea + syphilis + HSV + HIV; treat per CDC;

(8) IBD considerations: if persistent, systemic symptoms, atypical features → endoscopy + biopsy + workup;

