Hyponatremia Workup + Management Primary Care:

(1) Severity: mild (Na 130-134), moderate (125-129), severe (< 125); symptoms guide urgency (confusion, seizure, coma);

(2) Volume status assessment key:
  • Hypovolemic — diuretics, GI loss, third spacing, adrenal insufficiency;
  • Euvolemic (this patient) — SIADH most common cause (drugs — SSRI, carbamazepine, opioids, antipsychotics; lung — TB, pneumonia, small cell CA; CNS — stroke, infection, mass; surgery; postoperative; nausea; pain; idiopathic), hypothyroidism, adrenal insufficiency, primary polydipsia, beer potomania, low solute intake;
  • Hypervolemic — HF, cirrhosis, nephrotic syndrome, CKD;

(3) Workup:
  • Serum osmolality (rule out pseudo / translocational):
  • Hypotonic (true hyponatremia, < 280): most cases;
  • Iso/hypertonic: hyperglycemia, mannitol, contrast, pseudohyponatremia (hypertriglyceridemia, paraproteinemia);
  • Urine osmolality (~ free water excretion ability):
  • Low (< 100) — primary polydipsia, beer potomania, low solute;
  • High (> 100) — ADH active — SIADH, hypovolemia, hypervolemia;
  • Urine Na: < 20 (hypovolemia, hypervolemia); > 40 (SIADH, diuretic, adrenal/thyroid);
  • TSH + cortisol (rule out treatable endocrine);
  • BUN, Cr, glucose;

(4) SIADH diagnosis: euvolemic, hypotonic hyponatremia, urine osm > 100 (inappropriate concentration), urine Na > 30, normal kidney + adrenal + thyroid, no diuretic use;

(5) Treatment principles — careful correction (RAPID correction → osmotic demyelination syndrome (ODS) — irreversible neuro damage, esp in chronic hyponatremia, malnutrition, hypokalemia, alcoholism, liver disease):
  • Severe / symptomatic (seizure, coma) acute: 3% saline 100 mL bolus IV may repeat; ICU; raise Na 4-6 mmol/L acutely;
  • Maximum correction: 8-10 mmol/L per 24 h, 18 mmol/L per 48 h (some say 6-8/24 h chronic, > 6 wk; lower in high-risk);
  • Mild-moderate chronic asymptomatic: address underlying cause;
  • SIADH treatment:
  • Fluid restriction (800-1200 mL/d) first-line;
  • Salt + protein intake (urea);
  • Loop diuretic + Na supplementation;
  • Vaptans (tolvaptan — V2 receptor antagonist) for refractory; cost + hepatotoxicity caution;
  • Demeclocycline alternative;
  • Discontinue offending drugs;

(6) Drug discontinuation review: SSRIs, thiazides, NSAIDs, opioids, carbamazepine, antipsychotics, MDMA;

(7) Address underlying cause: hypothyroid → replace; adrenal insufficiency → steroid; SIADH cause (infection, cancer, CNS);

(8) Outpatient follow-up close: recheck Na in 24-48 h initial then weekly;

(9) Hospitalization for severe / symptomatic / unable to correct outpatient / unstable;

(10) Multidisciplinary: PCP + nephrology + endocrine if SIADH workup + ED if severe
————————————————
Hyponatremia: volume + serum/urine osm + urine Na for diagnosis. SIADH common (drugs — SSRI; CNS; lung; postop). Careful correction to avoid ODS — max 8-10 mmol/L/24 h. Treat underlying + offending drugs. Severe → hypertonic saline ICU. Multidisciplinary.

