Immunocompromised Primary Care + Immunology Basics:

(1) Major types immunodeficiency:
  • Primary immunodeficiency (PID) — genetic (CVID, X-linked agammaglobulinemia, severe combined ID, complement deficiencies, hyper-IgM, Wiskott-Aldrich, ataxia-telangiectasia, chronic granulomatous disease, etc.); often detected childhood;
  • Secondary / acquired:
  • HIV;
  • Malignancy (especially hematologic — lymphoma, leukemia, myeloma);
  • Chemotherapy + targeted therapy (CD20 — rituximab; BTK; checkpoint inhibitors);
  • Immunosuppressants (steroids, calcineurin inhibitors, MMF, azathioprine, methotrexate, biologics — TNF, IL-6, IL-17, IL-23, B-cell, T-cell, JAK inhibitors);
  • Transplant (solid organ + HSCT);
  • Diabetes + uncontrolled hyperglycemia;
  • Splenectomy / asplenia (functional — sickle cell);
  • Malnutrition;
  • CKD / ESRD;
  • Cirrhosis;
  • Aging (immunosenescence);
  • Pregnancy (mild physiologic immunosuppression);

(2) Workup suspected:
  • Recurrent / unusual / severe infections;
  • Family history;
  • Quantitative immunoglobulins (IgG, IgA, IgM, IgE);
  • Lymphocyte subsets (CD3, CD4, CD8, CD19, CD56);
  • Vaccine response (T-cell-independent — Pneumovax; T-cell-dependent — tetanus);
  • Complement (CH50, C3, C4);
  • HIV;
  • Refer immunology specialist;

(3) Vaccinations in immunocompromised:
  • Generally AVOID live vaccines: MMR, varicella, yellow fever, oral typhoid, BCG, oral polio, smallpox (limited situations);
  • Recombinant Shingrix preferred over live Zostavax in immunocompromised — ACIP recommends ≥ 19 yo immunocompromised;
  • Inactivated vaccines safe but may have reduced response:
  • More doses or higher doses often (e.g., 4 doses HepB 40 mcg dialysis);
  • Pneumococcal: PCV20 or PCV15 + PPSV23 8 wk apart (vs 1 yr) for immunocompromised;
  • Vaccinate before immunosuppression when possible: 2-4 wk live vaccines, 2 wk inactivated;
  • HSCT recipients: revaccination protocols (lose immune memory);
  • Solid organ transplant: optimize before transplant; live vaccines avoided lifelong after;
  • Biologics specific:
  • Anti-CD20 (rituximab) — vaccinate ≥ 4 wk before; reduced response × 6 mo after;
  • Anti-TNF — reduced response; reasonable to vaccinate while on;
  • Steroid: > 20 mg prednisone × 2 wk = immunosuppressed;

(4) Infection prevention + prophylaxis:
  • PCP (Pneumocystis jirovecii) prophylaxis: TMP-SMX for HIV (CD4 < 200), post-transplant, certain chemo regimens, ANCA vasculitis, others;
  • CMV prophylaxis: post-transplant + selected;
  • Fungal prophylaxis: selected high-risk;
  • Toxoplasmosis for HIV (CD4 < 100);
  • Hand hygiene + masking + avoidance crowds + sick contacts;
  • Food safety + water + travel precautions;
  • Pet safety education (toxoplasmosis, salmonella);
  • Wound care prompt;
  • Dental care good hygiene;

(5) Recognition of infections:
  • May present atypically (less fever, less inflammation);
  • Lower threshold for evaluation + treatment;
  • Broad differentials (opportunistic + community);
  • Cultures + biopsies;
  • Empiric treatment broader;

(6) Specific situations:
  • Asplenia: vaccinate (encapsulated — pneumococcal, Hib, meningococcal ACWY + B), prophylactic antibiotic for some, medical alert ID, prompt evaluation fever + early empiric ceftriaxone;
  • Sickle cell: similar + penicillin prophylaxis childhood;
  • Neutropenic fever: emergency;
  • HIV + low CD4: opportunistic infection screening + prophylaxis; ART initiation;

(7) Cancer surveillance: immunocompromised at increased risk for several cancers — screening per protocols + appropriate;

(8) Mental health + caregiver support;

(9) Multidisciplinary: PCP + ID + immunology + transplant + oncology + relevant specialists + pharmacy + nursing + nutrition + behavioral health
————————————————
Immunocompromised: types (primary + secondary). Workup if recurrent/unusual. Vaccines: avoid live, more doses, recombinant Shingrix preferred. Infection prevention + prophylaxis (PCP, CMV, etc.). Atypical presentations — low threshold. Asplenia considerations. Multidisciplinary.

