Physical Activity Prescription + Exercise as Medicine (CDC + ACSM + DGA):

(1) Major impact: physical activity = one of most impactful interventions for prevention + treatment of chronic disease, mental health, mortality;

(2) CDC + DGA 2018 Physical Activity Guidelines:
  • Adults:
  • 150 min/wk moderate (brisk walking) OR 75 min/wk vigorous (jogging) OR combination;
  • Plus muscle-strengthening ≥ 2 d/wk (all major muscle groups);
  • More benefit with more — up to 300 min/wk;
  • Move more, sit less (sedentary behavior independent risk);
  • Older adults: above + balance training; modify per ability;
  • Children + adolescents: 60 min/d moderate-vigorous + muscle/bone strengthening 3x/wk;
  • Pregnancy + postpartum: 150 min/wk moderate; modify per stage;
  • Chronic conditions: still strongly recommended with adaptations;

(3) Exercise prescription components (FITT):
  • Frequency;
  • Intensity (talk test, HR zones, RPE);
  • Time (duration);
  • Type (aerobic, resistance, flexibility, balance);

(4) Intensity gauges:
  • Moderate: increased HR + breathing + sweat; can talk but not sing; ~ 50-70% HRmax;
  • Vigorous: significantly increased; only few words; ~ 70-85% HRmax;
  • Maximum HR: 220
  • age (rough);
  • MET-min/wk > 500 = adequate;

(5) Exercise as therapy — specific evidence:
  • Cardiovascular disease: cardiac rehab, prevention, post-event;
  • Hypertension: 5-10 mmHg BP reduction;
  • T2DM + prediabetes: improved insulin sensitivity, A1c reduction; DPP includes;
  • Dyslipidemia: HDL + TG improvement;
  • Obesity: weight + body composition + maintenance;
  • Cancer: prevention multiple cancers, during/after treatment improvement (fatigue, QOL, recurrence reduction breast/colon);
  • Mental health: depression (effective as antidepressants for mild-moderate), anxiety, cognition, dementia prevention;
  • Osteoporosis: weight-bearing + resistance for bone;
  • Osteoarthritis: paradoxically beneficial — exercise = first-line;
  • COPD: pulmonary rehab;
  • HF: cardiac rehab + exercise training;
  • PAD: structured exercise > revascularization for claudication (CLEVER);
  • Stroke recovery: rehab + ongoing;
  • Falls prevention: tai chi, multimodal;
  • Sleep: improves;
  • Mortality: dose-response — even small amounts reduce;

(6) Pre-exercise screening: ACSM updated — most healthy adults can begin without medical clearance; clearance for: known disease + symptoms + advanced age + intense activity;

(7) Specific populations:
  • Cardiac rehab Class I post-MI, stable angina, HF, post-CABG/PCI/valve, PAD;
  • Pulmonary rehab for COPD + ILD + others;
  • Cancer rehab survivorship;
  • Vestibular rehab;
  • Pelvic floor PT;
  • Vestibular + balance;
  • Children with disability;

(8) Behavior change principles (see separate): motivational interviewing, goal-setting, environmental, social, technology;

(9) Address barriers: time, access, safety, weather, mobility, knowledge, motivation, cost, social;

(10) Technology: wearables (Fitbit, Apple Watch, Garmin), apps, virtual programs, exergaming, gamification;

(11) Group + community programs: SilverSneakers (Medicare), local gyms, parks + recreation, walking groups, faith-based;

(12) Provider counseling effective: brief counseling + prescription + referral; Exercise is Medicine initiative;

