Sleep Medicine Basics + Primary Care (AASM):

(1) Sleep architecture: ~ 90 min cycles; NREM (N1, N2, N3 — deep) + REM (dreaming, memory consolidation); 4-6 cycles/night;

(2) Sleep duration recommendations (NSF + AAP):
  • Newborn 0-3 mo: 14-17 h;
  • Infant 4-11 mo: 12-15 h;
  • Toddler 1-2 yr: 11-14 h;
  • Preschool 3-5 yr: 10-13 h;
  • School age 6-13 yr: 9-11 h;
  • Teen 14-17 yr: 8-10 h (often inadequate — early school start times, screens);
  • Adult 18-64: 7-9 h;
  • Older adult ≥ 65: 7-8 h;

(3) Sleep deprivation effects:
  • Acute: cognition, mood, immune, metabolic;
  • Chronic (< 7 h adult): increased mortality, CV disease, DM, obesity, mental health, accidents (drowsy driving = drunk driving), cancer (shift work IARC group 2A);

(4) Sleep hygiene — foundation:
  • Regular schedule (even weekends);
  • Dark, cool, quiet bedroom (60-67°F);
  • Bed for sleep + sex only;
  • Avoid screens 1+ h before bed (blue light);
  • Caffeine cutoff afternoon;
  • Alcohol disrupts;
  • Exercise (not late);
  • Limit naps (< 30 min, early);
  • Sunlight exposure morning;
  • Relaxation routine;
  • Manage stress;

(5) Major sleep disorders primary care:
  • Insomnia disorder — see separate (CBT-I first-line);
  • OSA — see separate (CPAP + lifestyle + GLP-1 emerging);
  • Central sleep apnea — HF, opioid, idiopathic;
  • Restless Legs Syndrome (RLS) / Willis-Ekbom: urge to move + dysesthesia + evening + relief with movement; Workup: ferritin (target > 75-100, supplement), Cr, glucose, thyroid; Treatment: iron repletion if low; alpha-2-delta ligands (gabapentin, pregabalin — first-line shift); dopamine agonists (pramipexole, ropinirole — augmentation issue, less preferred now); rotigotine patch; opioids low-dose refractory;
  • Narcolepsy: excessive daytime sleepiness + cataplexy (type 1) + sleep paralysis + hypnagogic hallucinations; polysomnography + MSLT; modafinil/armodafinil, sodium oxybate, pitolisant, solriamfetol; refer sleep medicine;
  • Circadian rhythm disorders: delayed/advanced sleep phase, shift work, jet lag, irregular; melatonin + light therapy + chronotherapy;
  • Parasomnias: sleepwalking, night terrors, REM behavior disorder (alpha-synucleinopathy risk — Parkinson, DLB, MSA progression);
  • Hypersomnia disorders: idiopathic, Kleine-Levin;
  • Bruxism: dental + stress;
  • Sleep-related movement disorders: PLMS;

(6) Pediatric sleep:
  • Sleep training (multiple methods debated);
  • SIDS prevention (back to sleep, firm surface, no co-sleeping same bed, no soft objects);
  • OSA in children — adenotonsillectomy first-line;
  • ADHD + sleep bidirectional;
  • Adolescent later chronotype + school start times advocacy;

(7) Pregnancy + postpartum: sleep changes; RLS common; OSA can develop; preeclampsia association;

(8) Mental health bidirectional: depression, anxiety, PTSD, bipolar — sleep disruption + treatment;

(9) Substance use + sleep: stimulants, alcohol, opioids, marijuana — affect sleep;

(10) Sleep + cognitive aging: deep sleep + glymphatic clearance + dementia prevention emerging evidence;

(11) Drowsy driving + occupational safety; commercial drivers OSA screening;

(12) Sleep tracking technology: wearables increasingly accurate; orthosomnia (anxiety from data);

(13) Multidisciplinary: PCP + sleep medicine + ENT (OSA pediatric) + dental sleep (oral appliance) + behavioral health (CBT-I) + neurology + cardiology
