Preventive Medicine Principles (USPSTF + CDC + Healthy People 2030):

(1) Levels of prevention:
  • Primary — prevent disease occurrence (vaccination, lifestyle modification, smoking cessation, fluoride, seatbelts);
  • Secondary — early detection + treatment (screening — cancer, BP, glucose);
  • Tertiary — limit complications of existing disease (cardiac rehab, glycemic control to prevent complications);
  • Quaternary — protect from harms of medicine itself (avoid overtesting, overtreatment, overdiagnosis);

(2) USPSTF grades:
  • A strong recommendation high certainty net benefit;
  • B moderate certainty;
  • C small net benefit — individual decision;
  • D recommend against;
  • I insufficient evidence;
  • A + B routinely cover preventive services under ACA without cost-sharing;

(3) Key USPSTF preventive recommendations adults:
  • BP screening all adults ≥ 18;
  • Cholesterol screening age-based;
  • DM screening 35-70 + overweight;
  • Cancer screening:
  • Cervical 21-65;
  • Breast 40-74 biennial (USPSTF 2024 lowered to 40);
  • Colorectal 45-75 (lowered from 50);
  • Lung 50-80 with 20 pack-year history;
  • Prostate 55-69 shared decision;
  • Cervical, skin (selected), oral;
  • Osteoporosis women 65+ (younger if risk);
  • AAA men 65-75 ever-smoker;
  • Hepatitis C all adults 18-79;
  • Hepatitis B all adults (2023);
  • HIV 15-65;
  • Latent TB at-risk;
  • STIs risk-based;
  • Depression all adults including pregnant + postpartum;
  • Anxiety adults < 65 (USPSTF 2023);
  • Substance use alcohol + drugs + tobacco;
  • IPV women reproductive age;
  • Falls ≥ 65;
  • Lifestyle counseling weight, exercise, diet, smoking;

(4) Vaccinations per CDC schedule (see separate);

(5) Choosing Wisely / Quaternary prevention: avoid:
  • Unnecessary cancer screening (older, low risk, less benefit);
  • Routine imaging headache, LBP;
  • Routine EKG/CXR asymptomatic;
  • Annual physical detailed labs not evidence-based;
  • Antibiotic for viral;
  • PPI long-term without indication;
  • Polypharmacy without rationale;
  • Cancer screening with limited life expectancy;

(6) Shared decision-making essential for many — especially C-grade or where benefits/harms close;

(7) Risk assessment + stratification: Pooled Cohort Equations, FRAX, Tyrer-Cuzick, Lung CA risk, etc.;

(8) Counseling effective in primary care — even brief (e.g., smoking cessation 5 As, alcohol SBIRT);

(9) Population health + community level: water fluoridation, immunization programs, tobacco policy, food labeling, built environment, school health, workplace wellness;

(10) Health equity in prevention: stratify outcomes + address disparities;

(11) Healthy People 2030 framework: leading health indicators across domains;

(12) Implementation in practice: EHR reminders, team-based delivery, registries, outreach;

(13) Pediatric preventive (Bright Futures):
  • Vaccines per CDC;
  • Growth + development;
  • Lead, lipid, anemia, dental, vision/hearing screening;
  • Anticipatory guidance;

(14) Multidisciplinary: PCP + nursing + APP + behavioral health + dietitian + public health + community + school + workplace + family
