Patient Safety + Just Culture (IHI + AHRQ + IOM):

(1) Magnitude: medical errors ~ 3rd leading cause of death US (Makary BMJ 2016 estimate ~ 250,000/yr); primary care + ambulatory errors common but less studied;

(2) IOM (now NAM) framework — 'To Err is Human' (1999) + 'Crossing the Quality Chasm' (2001):
  • System problem, not individual;
  • Build safer systems;
  • 6 aims: Safe + Effective + Patient-centered + Timely + Efficient + Equitable; - 'Quintuple Aim' adds clinician well-being + equity;

(3) Just culture:
  • Distinguish:
  • Human error (slip, lapse) → console + system fix;
  • At-risk behavior (taking shortcut) → coach;
  • Reckless behavior (knowing risk) → discipline;
  • Psychological safety — speak up about safety without fear;
  • Learning culture > blame culture;
  • Reduces underreporting + improves system improvement;

(4) High-Reliability Organization (HRO) principles (Weick + Sutcliffe):
  • Preoccupation with failure;
  • Reluctance to simplify;
  • Sensitivity to operations;
  • Commitment to resilience;
  • Deference to expertise;

(5) Common error categories primary care:
  • Diagnostic errors — missed, delayed, wrong (especially cancer, MI, stroke, infection, PE) — leading cause primary care malpractice;
  • Medication errors — prescribing, dispensing, monitoring, communication;
  • Communication failures: handoffs, results, between team;
  • Care coordination + referrals: lost referrals, missed results;
  • Test result management: missed abnormal results most common;
  • Documentation: unclear, illegible (less now), missing;
  • Follow-up failures;
  • Care transitions: hospital-to-home, between settings;

(6) System solutions:
  • Closed-loop communication: results → patient → action → documentation;
  • Robust safety net systems: EHR reminders, automated follow-up, recall systems, panel management;
  • Standardization + checklists: surgical safety, central line, OB, sepsis, NEW for primary care;
  • Decision support: EHR alerts, clinical pathways, decision aids;
  • Medication safety: e-prescribing, drug interaction checking, medication reconciliation, double-checks for high-risk;
  • Read-back + verification;
  • Adequate staffing + workload;
  • Fatigue + burnout reduction;

(7) Reporting + analysis:
  • Voluntary incident reporting (low-threshold, blame-free) + system feedback;
  • Root cause analysis (RCA) for serious events — identify system causes;
  • Failure modes + effects analysis (FMEA) prospective risk identification;
  • Mortality + morbidity conferences — learning oriented;
  • AHRQ Common Formats standardized;

(8) Disclosure of errors:
  • Ethical + legal (most jurisdictions);
  • CANDOR program — Communication and Optimal Resolution;
  • Empathic, honest, system focus;
  • Reduces litigation when done well;
  • Apology laws (varies);

(9) Patient engagement in safety:
  • Speak up programs;
  • Medication reconciliation involvement;
  • Question + understand care;
  • Patient + family advisory councils;

(10) Health literacy + plain language essential;

(11) Specific safety priorities WHO, AHRQ, Joint Commission goals:
  • Patient ID;
  • Communication of test results / handoffs;
  • Medication safety (high-alert);
  • Infection prevention;
  • Falls;
  • Surgical safety;
  • Suicide prevention;
  • DVT prophylaxis;
  • Sepsis recognition;

(12) Outpatient-specific safety: telephone advice protocols, after-hours coverage, cross-coverage, test results management, abnormal result tracking, no-show follow-up, controlled substances;

(13) Clinician well-being + safety: 2nd victim phenomenon (clinician trauma after adverse event); peer support, debriefing;

(14) Resources: IHI, AHRQ PSNet, Joint Commission, state QIOs, NPSF (now part of IHI);

(15) Multidisciplinary: clinicians + risk + quality + patients + administration + IT + nursing + pharmacy + legal + insurance
————————————————
Patient safety: system focus (IOM). Just culture (distinguish human error, at-risk, reckless). HRO principles. Common errors (diagnostic, medication, communication, results). System solutions (closed-loop, checklists, decision support). CANDOR disclosure. Patient engagement. Wellbeing — 2nd victim. Multidisciplinary.

