Telemedicine in Primary Care — Best Practices (ATA + AAFP):

(1) Modalities:
  • Synchronous video: real-time, most like in-person;
  • Synchronous audio: telephone only;
  • Asynchronous (store + forward): patient submits photo/info;
  • Remote patient monitoring (RPM): BP, glucose, weight, SpO2, ECG, wearables;
  • eVisits: messaging-based;
  • eConsults: provider-to-provider (see separate);

(2) Appropriate use cases:
  • Routine chronic disease follow-up (HTN, DM, lipid);
  • Behavioral health (depression, anxiety, substance use, therapy);
  • Medication management + refills;
  • Minor acute conditions (URI, skin rashes, UTI selected);
  • Follow-up after labs/imaging;
  • Lifestyle counseling;
  • Care management + coordination;
  • Pre + post-procedural;
  • Specialty consultations;
  • Post-acute / hospital follow-up;
  • Rural + access-limited;

(3) Not appropriate:
  • Acute serious conditions needing physical exam;
  • Procedures;
  • Imaging-required diagnoses;
  • When physical exam essential;
  • Some sensitive issues (preferences vary);
  • Technology / language barriers severe;

(4) Best practices visit conduct:
  • Pre-visit: technology check, privacy/HIPAA, intake forms, consent;
  • Setting: quiet, well-lit, eye-level camera, professional appearance;
  • Introduction: identify self + confirm patient identity + setting privacy + explain technology;
  • Webside manner: eye contact (look at camera), unhurried, attentive, address technology issues;
  • Limited physical exam adapted: visual inspection, patient-performed maneuvers (palpation, ROM), home BP/wt/temp, smartphone tools;
  • Documentation: telemedicine modality + duration + key findings;
  • Follow-up + close the loop;

(5) Technology considerations:
  • Platforms: Epic MyChart Video, Doxy.me, Zoom for Healthcare, others; HIPAA-compliant;
  • Patient access: smartphone, tablet, computer; broadband;
  • Alternatives for digital divide: telephone, in-person;
  • Backup plan for technical issues;
  • Patient portal integration;

