Group Visits / Shared Medical Appointments (SMA) Integrative Care:

(1) Definition: physician-led group visit where multiple patients with similar conditions receive medical care + education + peer support together; can include other team members;

(2) Evidence: improved outcomes T2DM, HTN, HF, depression, chronic pain, prenatal care, weight management; cost-effective;

(3) Models:
  • Drop-in Group Medical Appointment (DIGMA): ongoing, mixed conditions, regular schedule;
  • Cooperative Health Care Clinic (CHCC): closed cohort same patients over time;
  • Physical SMA (PSMA): includes individual physical exam component;
  • Specialty + condition-specific: prenatal (Centering Pregnancy), DM, HTN, HF, depression, pain, weight, smoking cessation, behavioral health;

(4) Components:
  • Group education by team;
  • Peer interaction + support;
  • Individual physician encounter within or separate;
  • Team-based care — RN, dietitian, behavioral health, pharmacy as needed;
  • Goal-setting + accountability;
  • Self-management focus;
  • Cultural + language matching when possible;

(5) Advantages:
  • Patient: peer support + learning, more time with provider (90 min vs 15), normalization, accountability, social connection;
  • Provider: education efficiency, address common issues once, team-based, reduced burnout;
  • System: efficiency, access, reduced ED visits + hospitalizations, cost-effective;
  • Outcomes: improved A1c, BP, adherence, self-efficacy, satisfaction;

(6) Setup considerations:
  • Space: large enough for group + privacy;
  • Time: 90-120 min typical;
  • Frequency: weekly to monthly;
  • Group size: 6-15 typical;
  • Recruitment: screen + enroll, address transportation, scheduling;
  • Confidentiality + ground rules: HIPAA, group agreements;
  • Documentation: each individual encounter;
  • Billing: typically code each individual; some states offer specific codes;
  • Technology: virtual SMA growing — telegroups;

(7) Patient selection:
  • Common diagnosis or interest;
  • Mix of stages (engagement + role model);
  • Voluntary;
  • Address barriers;

(8) Specific examples + evidence:
