Behavioral Health Integration (BHI) — Collaborative Care Model (Unützer + APA + AIMS Center):

(1) Need: mental health in primary care; ~ 50% mental health care delivered in primary care; specialty access limited; outcomes traditionally suboptimal;

(2) Continuum of integration (SAMHSA-HRSA 4-quadrant):
  • Level 1: Minimal collaboration — separate;
  • Level 2: Basic collaboration at distance — referral with limited communication;
  • Level 3: Basic collaboration on-site — co-located;
  • Level 4: Close collaboration on-site with shared system;
  • Level 5: Close collaboration approaching integration;
  • Level 6: Full collaboration in transformed/merged integrated practice;
  • Higher level = better outcomes for moderate-severe conditions;

(3) Collaborative Care Model (CoCM) — most evidence:
  • 5 core principles:
  • Patient-centered team care;
  • Population-based care (registry);
  • Measurement-based care + treat-to-target (PHQ-9, GAD-7 routine);
  • Evidence-based care;
  • Accountable care;
  • Team members:
  • PCP — primary clinical management;
  • Behavioral Health Care Manager — RN, social worker, psychologist — care management, brief interventions, follow-up, registry;
  • Psychiatric Consultant — weekly case review with care manager, recommendations to PCP, direct consultation for complex;

(4) Evidence Collaborative Care: > 80 RCTs across conditions + settings — better outcomes vs usual care for depression, anxiety, substance use, PTSD, dementia + caregiver; pediatric; perinatal; chronic disease comorbid; veterans; rural;

(5) CMS Collaborative Care codes (BHI 99492-99494) support reimbursement; many private insurance;

(6) Implementation steps:
  • Assess practice readiness;
  • Identify champions + leadership;
  • Workflow design + EHR integration;
  • Hire/train care manager + psychiatric consultant;
  • Universal screening (PHQ-9, GAD-7, CRAFFT, others);
  • Registry + measurement;
  • Quality improvement ongoing;
  • Patient engagement;
  • Reimbursement strategy;

(7) Alternative integrated models:
  • Primary Care Behavioral Health (PCBH) — behavioral health provider embedded; brief interventions; warm handoffs; broader population; less specialized depression focus;
  • Co-location without integration — basic;
  • Bidirectional integration — primary care in mental health settings;

(8) Specific applications:
  • Depression — most evidence;
  • Anxiety;
  • PTSD + trauma;
  • Substance use disorders: MAT for OUD (buprenorphine), AUD pharmacotherapy + counseling;
  • Chronic pain + mental health comorbidity;
  • Severe mental illness in primary care: schizophrenia, bipolar; primary care of medical comorbidities + co-management with psychiatry;
  • Pediatric: family-based, school integration;
  • Perinatal: postpartum depression;
  • Geriatric: depression, dementia, caregiver support;
  • Substance use disorders: SBIRT + MAT;
  • Chronic disease: DM + depression, etc. — depression treatment improves both;

(9) Specific evidence-based interventions delivered by BHI team:
  • Brief CBT;
  • Behavioral activation;
  • Problem-solving therapy;
  • Motivational interviewing;
  • Mindfulness;
  • Sleep hygiene + CBT-I;
  • Substance use brief intervention;
  • Self-management coaching;

(10) Pharmacotherapy support: PCP-prescribed with consultation; medication monitoring; adherence support;

(11) Quality measures: PHQ-9 response + remission, GAD-7, screening rates, treatment initiation + intensification, suicide risk assessment;

(12) Equity + access: BHI improves access to mental health especially for underserved + minorities + rural; addresses stigma;

(13) Technology: tele-mental health, apps (Calm, Headspace, computerized CBT — Beating the Blues), digital therapeutics;

(14) Workforce considerations: care manager workforce + training + reimbursement adequate; psychiatry workforce shortage so consultation model efficient;

(15) Resources: AIMS Center (University of Washington), APA Integrated Care, SAMHSA-HRSA Center for Integrated Health Solutions;

(16) Multidisciplinary: PCP + behavioral health care manager + psychiatric consultant + APP + nursing + social work + community resources + family + patient + payers + leadership
