Outpatient Hyperkalemia Management:

(1) Severity: mild 5.5-5.9, moderate 6.0-6.4, severe ≥ 6.5 or any ECG changes or symptoms — affects urgency;

(2) Confirm: rule out pseudohyperkalemia (hemolysis, prolonged tourniquet, fist clenching, K-EDTA contamination, thrombocytosis, leukocytosis) — repeat properly + plasma vs serum if concern;

(3) ECG indications: K ≥ 6, symptoms, rapid change; look for peaked T waves → loss of P → wide QRS → sine wave (severe); ECG changes need IMMEDIATE treatment regardless of level;

(4) Causes:
  • Renal — CKD, AKI;
  • Medications (most common modifiable in outpatient): ACEi/ARB, K-sparing diuretics (spironolactone, eplerenone, amiloride), MRA (finerenone), TMP-SMX, NSAIDs, heparin, beta-blockers, calcineurin inhibitors, succinylcholine;
  • Adrenal insufficiency;
  • Acidosis;
  • Hyperglycemia (insulin deficiency);
  • Cell breakdown (rhabdo, tumor lysis, hemolysis);
  • Excess intake usually with kidney impairment;

(5) Asymptomatic mild-moderate without ECG changes (this patient) outpatient:
  • Dietary K restriction counseling (limit bananas, potatoes, tomatoes, oranges, melon, spinach, beans, salt substitutes — KCl content);
  • Loop diuretic (furosemide) — kaliuretic;
  • K binders — modern outpatient option:
  • Patiromer (Veltassa) — non-absorbable polymer; slow onset; good for chronic; allows continuation RAAS therapy;
  • Sodium zirconium cyclosilicate (Lokelma) — newer, faster onset;
  • SPS (Kayexalate) — older, GI side effects (concern bowel ischemia); replaced by newer agents often;
  • Address underlying: adjust offending medications (don't blindly stop ACEi in HF/CKD — assess benefit-risk; new binders allow continuation);
  • Treat acidosis if present (bicarbonate selected);

