Carpal Tunnel Syndrome (AAOS + AAN):

(1) Diagnosis clinical primarily:
  • Symptoms: median nerve distribution numbness/paresthesia (thumb, index, middle, lateral ring), often worse at night/with activities, hand shaking relief, weakness/clumsiness;
  • Provocative tests: Phalen (90 sec wrist flexion), Tinel (percuss median nerve), Durkan compression (most specific); thenar atrophy (severe/chronic);

(2) Risk factors: F > M, age, obesity, pregnancy, DM, hypothyroidism, RA, dialysis, amyloidosis, repetitive wrist activities, vibration;

(3) Differential: cervical radiculopathy (C6-7), thoracic outlet, ulnar neuropathy, peripheral neuropathy, brachial plexopathy;

(4) Workup:
  • Clinical diagnosis sufficient many cases;
  • EMG/NCS — gold standard if uncertain, severe, surgical consideration, refractory, atypical, occupational/legal documentation;
  • US of median nerve — increasingly used (cross-sectional area ≥ 9-10 mm²);
  • MRI atypical;
  • Labs selectively: TSH (hypothyroid), HbA1c (DM), CBC + RF + ANA (autoimmune), vit B12; pregnancy assessment;

(5) Conservative management first (mild-moderate):
  • Wrist splinting (neutral position) — especially nighttime; modest evidence;
  • Activity modification + ergonomics: keyboard, mouse, repetitive grip; workplace;
  • NSAIDs / acetaminophen for symptoms;
  • Local corticosteroid injection (1-2/yr) — short-term effective;
  • Oral corticosteroid short course — modest evidence;
  • PT — nerve gliding exercises;
  • Address underlying: treat hypothyroid, glucose control;

(6) Surgery (open or endoscopic carpal tunnel release) for:
  • Severe / persistent / refractory;
  • Significant motor weakness or atrophy;
  • Severe sensory loss;
  • Failure conservative;
  • High-risk for permanent dysfunction;
  • Effective + outpatient procedure;

(7) Postoperative: PT, gradual return to activity, expect improvement weeks-months;

(8) Pregnancy-related: usually resolves postpartum — conservative (splint);

(9) Occupational considerations: ergonomic assessment, workplace modification, workers' compensation if applicable;

(10) Multidisciplinary: PCP + hand surgeon (ortho or plastic) + PT/OT + occupational medicine if work-related
