Chronic Otitis Media Management (AAO-HNS):

(1) Chronic suppurative otitis media (CSOM): chronic TM perforation + intermittent/persistent otorrhea ≥ 2 wk;

(2) Cholesteatoma — separate entity, can be congenital or acquired (more concerning): keratinized squamous epithelium in middle ear; can erode bone + cause complications (hearing loss, CN VII palsy, vertigo, meningitis, brain abscess, lateral sinus thrombosis); white/pearly mass in retraction pocket; CT temporal bone for evaluation + extent;

(3) Workup: otoscopy + microsuction; pneumatic otoscopy / tympanometry (limited if perf); audiogram; cultures of drainage; CT temporal bone for cholesteatoma / complications;

(4) Medical management:
  • Topical antibiotic drops with steroid: ofloxacin (Floxin), ciprofloxacin + dexamethasone (Ciprodex) — safe with perforation;
  • Avoid aminoglycoside drops with perforation (potentially ototoxic);
  • Aural toilet (debridement, suction);
  • Keep ear dry — water precautions;
  • Treat 7-14 d typically; chronic may need longer;

(5) Surgical management:
  • Cholesteatoma — surgical removal (tympanomastoidectomy) — essential to prevent complications;
  • Persistent perforation with hearing loss or recurrent infection → tympanoplasty;
  • Mastoiditis acute or chronic — IV abx + surgery if severe;
  • ENT specialty management;

(6) Hearing loss management: hearing aids, BAHA (bone anchored), CI selected;

(7) Complications watch:
  • Mastoiditis;
  • Facial palsy;
  • Labyrinthitis (vertigo + sensorineural HL);
  • Petrositis (Gradenigo's triad — otorrhea + retro-orbital pain + abducens palsy);
  • Meningitis;
  • Brain abscess;
  • Lateral sinus thrombosis;
  • Otitic hydrocephalus;
  • These are emergencies;

(8) Pediatric considerations: chronic OM with effusion (OME) — tympanostomy tubes if persistent; speech delay;

(9) Multidisciplinary: PCP + ENT + audiology + speech pathology + neurosurgery if complications
